<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="47" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1436,1670,2006]" pageId="13" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,330,1670,1696]" pageId="13" pageNumber="47">Etymology</emphasis>
. From the Greek, 
<emphasis box="[545,602,1671,1696]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="47">pilos</emphasis>
(hair), in reference to the hind tibia having a feathering of dense, long, fine setae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="48" pageId="13" pageNumber="47" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1436,1670,2006]" pageId="13" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,340,1747,1773]" pageId="13" pageNumber="47">Comments.</emphasis>
The remains of four of these flies in such a minute piece of amber indicate they were either congregating at a resin flux or were swarming. Swarms in empidoids and other 
<taxonomicName box="[1083,1171,1786,1812]" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Diptera</taxonomicName>
are usually comprised of males, into which females fly to become mated. The eyes of male Eremoneura that swarm are typically holoptic, but those of Chimeromyiidae are not.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1436,1670,2006]" pageId="13" pageNumber="47">
This species appears to be one of the most primitive species of 
<emphasis box="[991,1157,1903,1928]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="47">Chimeromyia</emphasis>
, by plesiomorphically possessing a fairly well developed anal lobe at the base of the wing. In those empidoids that have crossveins bm-cu and r-m nearly contiguous (e.g., some extant tachydromiines), bm-cu is usually distal to r-m, unlike 
<emphasis box="[1409,1436,1980,2005]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="47">C.</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,152,216]" pageId="14" pageNumber="48">
<taxonomicName box="[151,245,152,177]" class="Insecta" family="Opetiidae" genus="Chimeromyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pilitibia">
<emphasis box="[151,245,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="48">pilitibia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
where bm-cu is slightly proximal to r-m. The primitive new genus 
<emphasis box="[1054,1237,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="48">
<taxonomicName box="[1054,1232,152,177]" class="Insecta" family="Opetiidae" genus="Chimeromyina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">Chimeromyina</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
however, shares the same configuration of crossveins with 
<emphasis box="[647,813,191,216]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="48">Chimeromyia.</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
